comments.body: Also, almost all of the condors are marked with wing bands so usually that helps in indentification.

I agree it would be unusual to find one during late fall/early winter but the date of the observation says Jun 24, 2016 and the submission date is Dec 29, 2017. Seeing  a Turkey Vulture in the canyon in June would not be unheard of and are fairly common. I still believe this is a Turkey Vulture just based on what I’m seeing. The overall shape of the bird, slight gray/silver primaries/secondaries, and long wedge shape tail is characteristic of a Turkey Vulture.
If you are using the phone app hit the location and you can move your site location

I am new to this website and also on the on ramp to the super highway. I could not figure out how to update the location of my observation.  I am also the person who took the shots you guys are talking about. I was on a private raft trip down the Colorado R. near Columbine Falls on the Hualapai Indian Reservation when I took the Pics. All of the 16 people I was with agreed that these were Condors because of their size. Hope this info may help in an I.D. Bob
I double checked on where the siting was which is near the Grand Canyon but the other features of this bird still lead me to believe this is a Turkey Vulture.
